==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skit
<hw>Skit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>skit</ets>to slide, as adj., hasty, precipitate, of Scand. origin,
and akin to E. <ets>shoot</ets>, v.t.; cf. Icel. <ets>skyti</ets>,
<ets>skytja</ets>, <ets>skytta</ets>, a marksman, shooter,
<ets>skj⟦omac⟧ta</ets> to shoot, <ets>sk⟦umac⟧ta</ets> a taunt.
⟦root⟧159. See <er>Shoot</er>.]</ety> <def>To cast reflections on; to
asperse.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Crose.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skit
<hw>Skit</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A reflection; a jeer or
gibe; a sally; a brief satire; a squib.</def>
<rj><au>Tooke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A similar vein satire upon the emptiness of writers is given in
his ⟦ldquo⟧Tritical Essay upon the Faculties of the Human Mind;⟦rdquo⟧
but that is a mere <qex>skit</qex> compared with this strange
performance.</q> <rj><qau>Leslie Stephen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A wanton girl; a light wench.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A short theatrical presentation, often comical or
satirical. Comical <ex>skits</ex> are sometimes presented by amateur or
ad hoc groups at parties, dinners, or other social gatherings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skitter</ent>⟦br⟧
